{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772181444811,"sessionID":"ses_361c37f15ffeuVWV0XN4ZPvLel","part":{"id":"prt_c9e3ed5830012u0Mw2AXlhVkBQ","sessionID":"ses_361c37f15ffeuVWV0XN4ZPvLel","messageID":"msg_c9e3ecd1a001TvANwvLES6fB99","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_01SYGri4vaXAAktCLpsHtcRJ","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/CONVENTIONS.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/CONVENTIONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Spec Conventions\n2: \n3: This document defines the rules, terminology, and templates that all documents\n4: under `spec/` must follow.\n5: \n6: ## Clean-Room Rules\n7: \n8: All spec documents are produced by reverse engineering — reading observable\n9: artifacts (source code, runtime logs, CLI output) rather than relying on\n10: undocumented design intent. The following rules enforce that constraint.\n11: \n12: 1. **Cite observable evidence.** Every behavioral claim must reference a source\n13:    location (file and line range) or a reproducible runtime observation.\n14: 2. **Never infer intent.** Describe what the code does, not why the author\n15:    chose to do it that way.\n16: 3. **Distinguish levels of confidence.** Use the confidence labels defined\n17:    below on any claim that is not directly confirmed by code.\n18: 4. **Do not copy source code verbatim** beyond short illustrative snippets\n19:    (five lines or fewer). Paraphrase logic in prose or pseudocode.\n20: 5. **Flag gaps explicitly.** Use the Open Questions section rather than\n21:    speculating in the body of the document.\n22: 6. **Version your observations.** Record the commit SHA or date range of the\n23:    source examined at the top of each document.\n24: \n25: ## Confidence Labels\n26: \n27: Place a label inline after any claim whose certainty is less than direct\n28: code confirmation. Labels use the format `[CONFIDENCE: <level>]`.\n29: \n30: | Label | Meaning |\n31: | --- | --- |\n32: | `[CONFIRMED]` | Directly verified in source code (cite file:line). |\n33: | `[INFERRED]` | Logically follows from confirmed facts but not directly observed. |\n34: | `[ASSUMED]` | Reasonable assumption; plausible but unverified. |\n35: | `[UNKNOWN]` | Not determinable from available evidence; add to Open Questions. |\n36: \n37: Omit the label only when the entire statement is `[CONFIRMED]` and the\n38: citation is present in the same sentence.\n39: \n40: ## Terminology\n41: \n42: | Term | Definition |\n43: | --- | --- |\n44: | **bead** | A discrete unit of work tracked by the `br` CLI. |\n45: | **epic** | A parent bead that groups related child beads. |\n46: | **iteration** | One pass of the Ralph loop: select, prompt, execute, evaluate. |\n47: | **phase** | A top-level command (`reverse`, `decompose`, `forward`). |\n48: | **run** | A single invocation of a phase command, identified by a `runId`. |\n49: | **session** | The opencode SDK conversation context for one iteration. |\n50: | **skill** | A named question set or prompt variant used during reverse. |\n51: | **template** | A Handlebars `.hbs` file that generates an agent prompt. |\n52: \n53: When introducing a term not in this table, define it in the module doc and\n54: propose adding it here via a PR comment.\n55: \n56: ## Required Section Template\n57: \n58: Every module spec must include the following sections in this order. Omit a\n59: section only if it genuinely does not apply, and note the omission with\n60: `_Not applicable for this module._`\n61: \n62: ---\n63: \n64: ```markdown\n65: # <Module Name>\n66: \n67: > One-sentence description of the module's role in the system.\n68: \n69: **Source:** `src/<filename>.ts` (examined at commit `<sha>` / `<date>`)\n70: \n71: ## Purpose\n72: \n73: Two to four sentences. What problem does this module solve and where does it\n74: sit in the overall architecture?\n75: \n76: ## Triggers\n77: \n78: What causes this module to execute? List entry points: exported functions,\n79: CLI commands, or events that invoke this module. Cite source locations.\n80: \n81: ## Inputs\n82: \n83: | Name | Type | Source | Description |\n84: |---|---|---|---|\n85: | `<name>` | `<type>` | `<caller / env / file>` | What it represents |\n86: \n87: ## Outputs\n88: \n89: | Name | Type | Destination | Description |\n90: |---|---|---|---|\n91: | `<name>` | `<type>` | `<caller / file / stdout>` | What it represents |\n92: \n93: ## Side Effects\n94: \n95: List observable effects outside the return value: file writes, environment\n96: mutations, process exits, network calls, spawned child processes.\n97: \n98: ## Failure Modes\n99: \n100: | Condition | Behavior | Recovery |\n101: |---|---|---|\n102: | `<condition>` | `<what happens>` | `<how it is handled>` |\n103: \n104: ## Dependencies\n105: \n106: | Dependency | Type | Purpose |\n107: |---|---|---|\n108: | `<name>` | internal / npm / system | Why this module uses it |\n109: \n110: ## Open Questions\n111: \n112: - List anything that could not be determined from available evidence.\n113: ```\n114: \n115: ---\n116: \n117: ## Markdown Style\n118: \n119: - Use ATX-style headings (`#`, `##`, `###`). Never use Setext underlines.\n120: - Wrap prose at 80 characters. Code blocks and tables are exempt.\n121: - Use fenced code blocks with an explicit language tag.\n122: - Prefer ordered lists for sequential steps; unordered lists for\n123:   unordered items.\n124: - Do not use bare URLs. Wrap links in Markdown link syntax.\n125: - One blank line before and after every block element (heading, list,\n126:   table, code block).\n127: - Do not use trailing spaces for line breaks. Use a blank line or HTML\n128:   `<br>` only when necessary.\n129: \n130: ## File Naming\n131: \n132: - Use lowercase kebab-case: `run-state.md`, `output-parser.md`.\n133: - Match the source filename where possible (drop the `.ts` extension).\n134: - The two meta-documents (`README.md`, `CONVENTIONS.md`) are the only\n135:   permitted uppercase filenames in `spec/`.\n\n(End of file - total 135 lines)\n</content>","title":"spec/CONVENTIONS.md","metadata":{"preview":"# Spec Conventions\n\nThis document defines the rules, terminology, and templates that all documents\nunder `spec/` must follow.\n\n## Clean-Room Rules\n\nAll spec documents are produced by reverse engineering — reading observable\nartifacts (source code, runtime logs, CLI output) rather than relying on\nundocumented design intent. The following rules enforce that constraint.\n\n1. **Cite observable evidence.** Every behavioral claim must reference a source\n   location (file and line range) or a reproducible runtime observation.\n2. **Never infer intent.** Describe what the code does, not why the author\n   chose to do it that way.\n3. **Distinguish levels of confidence.** Use the confidence labels defined\n   below on any claim that is not directly confirmed by code.\n4. **Do not copy source code verbatim** beyond short illustrative snippets\n   (five lines or fewer). Paraphrase logic in prose or pseudocode.\n5. **Flag gaps explicitly.** Use the Open Questions section rather than","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772181444802,"end":1772181444810}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772181445227,"sessionID":"ses_361c37f15ffeuVWV0XN4ZPvLel","part":{"id":"prt_c9e3ed8c50019atDL5BcPb9eDT","sessionID":"ses_361c37f15ffeuVWV0XN4ZPvLel","messageID":"msg_c9e3ecd1a001TvANwvLES6fB99","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_01R8hFnPZmJUvcrX5VFy6jQM","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/workflows/core-workflows.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/workflows/core-workflows.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Core Workflows\n2: \n3: > Behavioral specification of the primary user-visible workflows in the\n4: > super-ralph agent framework, covering triggers, preconditions, normal flow,\n5: > alternate flows, failure outcomes, and observable outputs.\n6: \n7: **Source examined at commit:** `ecc95c0` (2026-02-27)\n8: \n9: ## Purpose\n10: \n11: This document captures the end-to-end behavior of each command a project\n12: operator can invoke. Each workflow section describes what the operator\n13: observes from the outside: what to provide, what happens in sequence, what\n14: changes on disk, and what can go wrong.\n15: \n16: For internal module interactions see\n17: [`spec/architecture/overview.md`](../architecture/overview.md) and\n18: [`spec/architecture/runtime-lifecycle.md`](../architecture/runtime-lifecycle.md).\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## WF-01: Project Initialization (`super-ralph init`)\n23: \n24: **Summary:** Scaffolds a project for first use. Must be run once before any\n25: phase command.\n26: \n27: ### Participating Modules\n28: \n29: - `src/init.ts` — orchestrates all scaffolding steps\n30: - `src/config.ts` — provides config defaults written to `config.toml`\n31: - `src/index.ts` — CLI dispatch\n32: \n33: ### Trigger\n34: \n35: The operator runs `super-ralph init` inside a project directory.\n36: \n37: ### Preconditions\n38: \n39: - `bun` is installed and on `PATH`. [CONFIRMED: `src/init.ts`]\n40: - `br` CLI is installed and on `PATH`. [CONFIRMED: `src/init.ts`]\n41: - The working directory is the intended project root.\n42: - `.super-ralph/` does not exist (idempotent if it does; existing files are\n43:   preserved).\n44: \n45: ### Normal Flow\n46: \n47: 1. `src/init.ts:runInit` creates `.super-ralph/` if it does not exist.\n48: 2. Five template files are copied from the CLI's `templates/` directory into\n49:    `.super-ralph/`. Any file that already exists at the destination is skipped.\n50: 3. `.super-ralph/config.toml` is written with defaults. The `cli.path` key is\n51:    set to the absolute path of `src/index.ts` as detected at runtime.\n52: 4. `.opencode/plugins/super-ralph.js` is created (the `task_complete` plugin).\n53:    `bun install` is run inside `.opencode/` to install its dependencies.\n54: 5. `tasks/` directory is created if absent.\n55: 6. If `.beads/` does not exist, `br init` is run to create the beads workspace.\n56: 7. `AGENTS.md` is created (or appended to) with a reference to\n57:    `.super-ralph/AGENTS.md`.\n58: \n59: ### Alternate Flow: Re-run on Initialized Project\n60: \n61: If `.super-ralph/` already exists, steps 2–7 are still attempted. Template\n62: files that already exist are skipped without error. `br init` is skipped if\n63: `.beads/` already exists. The command is safe to re-run.\n64: \n65: ### Failure Outcomes\n66: \n67: | Condition | Observed Behavior |\n68: | --- | --- |\n69: | `bun` not on `PATH` | Step 4 fails; `bun install` exits non-zero; error is printed to stderr |\n70: | `br` not on `PATH` | Step 6 fails; `br init` exits non-zero; error is printed to stderr |\n71: | Write permission denied on project root | File creation fails; error propagates to stderr |\n72: \n73: ### Observable Outputs and State Changes\n74: \n75: - `.super-ralph/` directory created.\n76: - `.super-ralph/config.toml` written with defaults.\n77: - `.super-ralph/forward.hbs`, `decompose.hbs`, `reverse.hbs` written.\n78: - `.super-ralph/intake-checklist.md` and `AGENTS.md` written.\n79: - `.opencode/plugins/super-ralph.js` written; `bun install` run in `.opencode/`.\n80: - `tasks/` directory created.\n81: - `.beads/` workspace initialized via `br init`.\n82: - `AGENTS.md` in the project root created or updated.\n83: - Exit code `0` on success; `1` on any error.\n84: \n85: ---\n86: \n87: ## WF-02: Spec Generation (`super-ralph reverse`)\n88: \n89: **Summary:** Elicits requirements from the operator (interactively or from\n90: provided inputs) and produces a Markdown spec file. Three sub-modes share\n91: the same command.\n92: \n93: ### Participating Modules\n94: \n95: - `src/reverse.ts` — phase orchestration and mode selection\n96: - `src/engine.ts` — loop execution for autonomous mode\n97: - `src/opencode.ts` — server lifecycle and prompt streaming\n98: - `src/interactive.ts` — SSE event interception and terminal prompts\n99: - `src/template.ts` — renders `reverse.hbs`\n100: - `src/skills.ts` — resolves skill content\n101: - `src/config.ts` — model resolution\n102: - `src/run-state.ts` — run artifact persistence\n103: - `src/progress.ts` — iteration progress log\n104: - `src/events.ts` — event emission and console output\n105: - `src/index.ts` — CLI dispatch\n106: \n107: ### Trigger\n108: \n109: The operator runs one of:\n110: \n111: ```text\n112: super-ralph reverse\n113: super-ralph reverse [inputs...] [options]\n114: super-ralph reverse [inputs...] --interactive [options]\n115: ```\n116: \n117: ### Preconditions\n118: \n119: - `super-ralph init` has been run in the project directory.\n120: - An opencode server can be started (API credentials available in the\n121:   environment) unless `--dry-run` is set.\n122: - If `--answers <path>` is supplied, the file exists and contains valid JSON.\n123: - If `--skill <path>` is supplied with a file path, that file exists and is\n124:   readable.\n125: \n126: ### Mode A: Interactive (no positional inputs)\n127: \n128: #### Normal Flow\n129: \n130: 1. `src/reverse.ts` detects no positional inputs and spawns an event-loop\n131:    that subscribes to SSE events from the opencode session.\n132: 2. `src/interactive.ts:runInteractiveSession` opens a session and sends the\n133:    rendered `reverse.hbs` prompt with `{{interactive}}` enabled.\n134: 3. When the agent emits a `question.asked` SSE event, `src/interactive.ts`\n135:    renders the question to the terminal using `@clack/prompts`.\n136: 4. The operator types or selects an answer; the answer is sent back to the\n137:    agent via `question.reply`.\n138: 5. Steps 3–4 repeat until the agent has collected enough information.\n139: 6. The agent synthesizes and writes a Markdown spec file to `docs/specs/`\n140:    (or `--output` directory) and calls `task_complete({ status: \"complete\" })`.\n141: 7. The session ends; the framework exits with code `0`.\n142: \n143: #### Alternate Flow: Mock Answers (`--answers <path>`)\n144: \n145: If `--answers <json>` is supplied, `src/interactive.ts:loadMockAnswers` reads\n146: the file. When a `question.asked` event fires, stored answers are replayed in\n147: order instead of prompting the terminal. Useful for automated testing.\n148: \n149: ### Mode B: Autonomous (positional inputs provided)\n150: \n151: #### Normal Flow\n152: \n153: 1. `src/reverse.ts` constructs `PhaseCallbacks` and calls\n154:    `src/engine.ts:runPhaseLoop`.\n155: 2. The engine loads config, creates a run tracker, and starts an opencode\n156:    server.\n157: 3. Each iteration: `nextIteration` renders `reverse.hbs` with the inputs,\n158:    optional skill content, and (on iterations > 1) the current spec file\n159:    content for refinement.\n160: 4. The agent creates or refines the spec file and calls `task_complete`.\n161: 5. If `status` is `\"complete\"` or `\"phase_done\"`, the loop exits.\n162: 6. The run tracker finalizes; the server shuts down.\n163: \n164: Maximum iterations: `--max-iterations` (default 20). [CONFIRMED: `src/reverse.ts`]\n165: \n166: ### Mode C: Mixed (inputs + `--interactive`)\n167: \n168: The operator provides both positional inputs and `--interactive`. The inputs\n169: are passed as context to the agent while the interactive question-answer flow\n170: is still used. Behavior otherwise follows Mode A.\n171: \n172: ### Failure Outcomes\n173: \n174: | Condition | Observed Behavior |\n175: | --- | --- |\n176: | No API credentials in environment | opencode server startup fails; error on stderr; exit `1` |\n177: | Agent does not call `task_complete` | Result is `stalled`; failure strategy applied (`retry`/`skip`/`abort`) |\n178: | Iteration limit reached | Loop exits with `failed > 0`; exit code `1` |\n179: | `--answers` file not found or invalid JSON | Error thrown before session starts; exit `1` |\n180: | Inactivity timeout (default 180 s) | Session aborted; result recorded as `timeout`; strategy applied |\n181: | Hard timeout (default 30 min) | Session aborted; result recorded as `timeout`; strategy applied |\n182: \n183: ### Observable Outputs and State Changes\n184: \n185: - Markdown spec file written to `docs/specs/<name>.md` (default) or\n186:   `--output <dir>/<name>.md`.\n187: - `.super-ralph/runs/<runId>/session.json` — run summary.\n188: - `.super-ralph/runs/<runId>/events.jsonl` — structured event log.\n189: - `.super-ralph/runs/<runId>/iterations/001-<label>.log` — transcript per\n190:   iteration.\n191: - `.super-ralph/progress.md` — iteration summary appended.\n192: - `.super-ralph/session.json` — live run state mirror updated.\n193: - Streaming text from the agent printed to stdout in real time.\n194: - Exit code `0` if `failed == 0`; `1` otherwise.\n195: \n196: ---\n197: \n198: ## WF-03: Spec Decomposition (`super-ralph decompose`)\n199: \n200: **Summary:** Reads a Markdown spec and creates a dependency-ordered set of\n201: beads (tasks) under a new epic via the `br` CLI.\n202: \n203: ### Participating Modules\n204: \n205: - `src/decompose.ts` — phase orchestration and bead creation logic\n206: - `src/engine.ts` — loop execution\n207: - `src/opencode.ts` — server lifecycle and prompt streaming\n208: - `src/beads.ts` — `br` CLI adapter\n209: - `src/template.ts` — renders `decompose.hbs`\n210: - `src/config.ts` — model resolution\n211: - `src/run-state.ts` — run artifact persistence\n212: - `src/progress.ts` — iteration progress log\n213: - `src/events.ts` — event emission and console output\n214: - `src/index.ts` — CLI dispatch\n215: \n216: ### Trigger\n217: \n218: ```text\n219: super-ralph decompose --spec <path> [options]\n220: ```\n221: \n222: ### Preconditions\n223: \n224: - `super-ralph init` has been run.\n225: - `--spec <path>` points to a readable Markdown file.\n226: - `br` CLI is on `PATH` and `.beads/` workspace is initialized.\n227: - opencode API credentials are available in the environment, unless\n228:   `--dry-run` is set.\n229: \n230: ### Normal Flow\n231: \n232: 1. `src/decompose.ts` reads the spec file content.\n233: 2. An epic bead is created via `br create --type epic` with the title from\n234:    `--epic-title` (or derived from the spec filename). The resulting epic ID\n235:    is stored in memory for all subsequent calls.\n236: 3. The engine starts an opencode server and begins the iteration loop.\n237: 4. Each iteration: `nextIteration` renders `decompose.hbs` with the spec\n238:    content, the epic ID, and the list of beads already created.\n239: 5. The agent analyzes the spec and the existing bead list, then calls `br\n240:    create` to add one bead. It sets `area:` labels, `depends:` fields, and\n241:    an appropriate title and description.\n242: 6. When the agent has created beads for all spec requirements, it calls\n243:    `task_complete({ status: \"phase_done\" })`.\n244: 7. Depending on config flags, additional beads may be appended:\n245:    review beads (`include_review`), bugscan beads (`include_bugscan`),\n246:    and an audit bead (`include_audit`). [CONFIRMED: `src/decompose.ts`]\n247: 8. The loop exits; the server shuts down.\n248: \n249: Maximum iterations: `--max-iterations` (default 50). [CONFIRMED: `src/decompose.ts`]\n250: \n251: ### Alternate Flow: Dry Run\n252: \n253: With `--dry-run`, the engine iterates `nextIteration` to show which bead\n254: would be created on each pass, but no opencode server starts and no `br\n255: create` calls are made. Exits `0`.\n256: \n257: ### Failure Outcomes\n258: \n259: | Condition | Observed Behavior |\n260: | --- | --- |\n261: | `--spec` file not found | Error on stderr before loop starts; exit `1` |\n262: | `br create` fails | Exception propagates; iteration recorded as `error`; strategy applied |\n263: | Agent does not call `task_complete` | Result is `stalled`; strategy applied |\n264: | Iteration limit reached | Loop exits; if any iterations failed, exit code `1` |\n265: | Epic creation fails | Error before loop; exit `1` |\n266: \n267: ### Observable Outputs and State Changes\n268: \n269: - New epic bead created in `.beads/` via `br`.\n270: - One child bead created per iteration in `.beads/` via `br`.\n271: - Optional review, bugscan, and audit beads appended.\n272: - `.super-ralph/runs/<runId>/` artifacts written.\n273: - `.super-ralph/progress.md` appended per iteration.\n274: - Streaming agent text printed to stdout.\n275: - Exit code `0` if `failed == 0`; `1` otherwise.\n276: \n277: ---\n278: \n279: ## WF-04: Implementation (`super-ralph forward`)\n280: \n281: **Summary:** Implements beads in dependency order. For each ready bead, an\n282: agent session is created, the bead is implemented and committed, and the bead\n283: is closed. The loop continues until no ready beads remain.\n284: \n285: ### Participating Modules\n286: \n287: - `src/forward.ts` — phase orchestration and bead selection\n288: - `src/engine.ts` — loop execution\n289: - `src/opencode.ts` — server lifecycle and prompt streaming\n290: - `src/beads.ts` — `br` CLI adapter\n291: - `src/template.ts` — renders `forward.hbs`\n292: - `src/config.ts` — model resolution (by area label)\n293: - `src/progress.ts` — recent progress for agent context\n294: - `src/run-state.ts` — run artifact persistence\n295: - `src/events.ts` — event emission and console output\n296: - `src/index.ts` — CLI dispatch\n297: \n298: ### Trigger\n299: \n300: ```text\n301: super-ralph forward --epic <epicId> [options]\n302: ```\n303: \n304: ### Preconditions\n305: \n306: - `super-ralph init` has been run.\n307: - `--epic <epicId>` refers to an existing epic in `.beads/`.\n308: - At least one child bead is in the `ready` state (dependencies satisfied).\n309: - opencode API credentials are available, unless `--dry-run` is set.\n310: - The project is a git repository (agents commit changes).\n311: \n312: ### Normal Flow\n313: \n314: 1. `src/forward.ts:setup` queries `br ready --epic <epicId>` to retrieve\n315:    ready beads and determines `maxIterations` (default: twice the bead count).\n316: 2. The engine starts an opencode server.\n317: 3. Each iteration: `nextIteration` calls `br ready` again to get the current\n318:    highest-priority ready bead.\n319: 4. `getBeadDetails` fetches full bead metadata (title, description, labels,\n320:    dependencies).\n321: 5. Recent progress entries are read from `.super-ralph/progress.md` via\n322:    `src/progress.ts:readRecentProgress`.\n323: 6. `forward.hbs` is rendered with all bead and progress data.\n324: 7. The model is resolved: CLI `--model` override, or `area:<X>` label mapped\n325:    to `[models.areas].X` in config, or `[models].default`.\n326: 8. The agent receives the prompt and executes an 11-step implementation\n327:    workflow (read progress → inspect bead → implement → quality gates →\n328:    self-review → commit → close bead → update progress → call\n329:    `task_complete`). [CONFIRMED: `templates/forward.hbs`]\n330: 9. After `task_complete({ status: \"complete\" })`, `handleResult` returns\n331:    `true` to continue the loop.\n332: 10. When `br ready` returns no beads, `nextIteration` returns `null`; the\n333:     loop exits normally.\n334: \n335: ### Alternate Flow: Agent Signals `phase_done`\n336: \n337: If the agent calls `task_complete({ status: \"phase_done\" })`, `handleResult`\n338: returns `false` and the loop exits cleanly. This is used when the agent\n339: determines all epic work is complete even if `br ready` would normally\n340: continue.\n341: \n342: ### Alternate Flow: bead Blocked\n343: \n344: If the agent calls `task_complete({ status: \"blocked\" })`, the iteration\n345: counter increments `skipped` (not `failed`) and the loop continues to the\n346: next ready bead. The blocked bead remains open in `.beads/`.\n347: \n348: ### Alternate Flow: Dry Run\n349: \n350: With `--dry-run`, the engine lists the sequence of beads that would be\n351: implemented without starting a server or running any agent sessions.\n352: \n353: ### Alternate Flow: Attach Mode\n354: \n355: With `--attach <url>`, the engine connects to an already-running opencode\n356: server instead of spawning one. The server is not shut down when the loop\n357: ends. [CONFIRMED: `src/engine.ts`]\n358: \n359: ### Failure Outcomes\n360: \n361: | Condition | Observed Behavior |\n362: | --- | --- |\n363: | No ready beads at startup | `nextIteration` returns `null` immediately; loop exits; `0` beads processed; exit `0` |\n364: | Agent does not call `task_complete` | Result is `stalled`; failure strategy applied |\n365: | Agent calls `task_complete({ status: \"failed\" })` | Failure strategy applied (`retry`/`skip`/`abort`) |\n366: | Iteration limit reached | Loop exits with `failed > 0`; exit code `1` |\n367: | `br` CLI not on `PATH` | Exception on first `nextIteration`; loop aborts; exit `1` |\n368: | Inactivity or hard timeout | Session aborted; result is `timeout`; strategy applied |\n369: \n370: ### Observable Outputs and State Changes\n371: \n372: - Source files in the project modified or created by the agent.\n373: - Git commits created by the agent (one per bead, [INFERRED] from template).\n374: - beads closed in `.beads/` via `br close <beadId>` [CONFIRMED: `templates/forward.hbs`].\n375: - `.super-ralph/progress.md` appended per iteration.\n376: - `.super-ralph/runs/<runId>/` artifacts written.\n377: - Streaming agent output printed to stdout.\n378: - Exit code `0` if `failed == 0`; `1` otherwise.\n379: \n380: ---\n381: \n382: ## WF-05: Run Status (`super-ralph status`)\n383: \n384: **Summary:** Reads and displays the state of a prior run or the current state\n385: of an epic's beads.\n386: \n387: ### Participating Modules\n388: \n389: - `src/run-status.ts` — reads run artifacts\n390: - `src/beads.ts` — queries bead state for `--epic` mode\n391: - `src/index.ts` — CLI dispatch\n392: \n393: ### Trigger\n394: \n395: ```text\n396: super-ralph status --run <runId>\n397: super-ralph status --run latest\n398: super-ralph status --epic <epicId>\n399: ```\n400: \n401: ### Preconditions\n402: \n403: - For `--run`: `.super-ralph/runs/` exists; the referenced run directory\n404:   (or `latest`) is present.\n405: - For `--epic`: `br` CLI is on `PATH`; `.beads/` workspace is initialized.\n406: \n407: ### Normal Flow: Run Mode\n408: \n409: 1. `src/run-status.ts:getRunStatus` resolves `\"latest\"` to the most recently\n410:    created run directory (sorted by `runId` which is epoch-prefixed).\n411: 2. `session.json` is read from the run directory.\n412: 3. Counters (completed, skipped, failed), status, iteration log, and\n413:    transcript path are returned and printed to stdout.\n414: \n415: ### Normal Flow: Epic Mode\n416: \n417: 1. `src/beads.ts:getEpicProgress` calls `br show --epic <epicId>` and\n418:    `br list --epic <epicId>` to obtain total, completed, and remaining counts.\n419: 2. In-progress and open beads are listed by title.\n420: 3. Results are printed to stdout.\n421: \n422: ### Failure Outcomes\n423: \n424: | Condition | Observed Behavior |\n425: | --- | --- |\n426: | `--run` refers to a non-existent run ID | Error on stderr; exit `1` |\n427: | `--run latest` with no runs present | Error on stderr; exit `1` |\n428: | `--epic` refers to an unknown epic | `br` CLI exits non-zero; error on stderr; exit `1` |\n429: \n430: ### Observable Outputs and State Changes\n431: \n432: - Read-only. No files are written.\n433: - Human-readable run summary or epic progress printed to stdout.\n434: - Exit code `0` on success; `1` on error.\n435: \n436: ---\n437: \n438: ## WF-06: Environment Validation (`super-ralph doctor`)\n439: \n440: **Summary:** Checks that all dependencies and project configuration are\n441: correct. Optionally repairs fixable issues.\n442: \n443: ### Participating Modules\n444: \n445: - `src/opencode.ts` — `checkBrokenSymlinks` and optionally `--fix`\n446: - `src/index.ts` — CLI dispatch (doctor logic is inline)\n447: \n448: ### Trigger\n449: \n450: ```text\n451: super-ralph doctor\n452: super-ralph doctor --fix\n453: ```\n454: \n455: ### Preconditions\n456: \n457: None. `doctor` is designed to be run before or instead of `init`.\n458: \n459: ### Normal Flow\n460: \n461: The command checks the following items in order. Each item is printed as\n462: pass or fail:\n463: \n464: 1. `bun` binary reachable on `PATH`.\n465: 2. `br` CLI binary reachable on `PATH`.\n466: 3. `.super-ralph/` directory exists.\n467: 4. All three `.hbs` template files exist in `.super-ralph/`.\n468: 5. `.super-ralph/config.toml` is readable and valid TOML.\n469: 6. `.beads/` workspace directory exists.\n470: 7. `config.toml:cli.path` points to a readable file.\n471: 8. Broken symlinks under `~/.config/opencode/` are detected.\n472: \n473: With `--fix`: broken symlinks detected in step 8 are removed.\n474: \n475: ### Failure Outcomes\n476: \n477: | Condition | Observed Behavior |\n478: | --- | --- |\n479: | Any check fails | That check is printed as failed; overall exit code `1` |\n480: | All checks pass | Exit code `0` |\n481: | `--fix` removes a symlink | A line reporting the removed path is printed to stdout |\n482: \n483: ### Observable Outputs and State Changes\n484: \n485: - With `--fix`: broken symlinks under `~/.config/opencode/` removed.\n486: - Without `--fix`: read-only.\n487: - Pass/fail summary printed to stdout per check.\n488: - Exit code `0` if all checks pass; `1` if any fail.\n489: \n490: ---\n491: \n492: ## WF-07: Agent Completion Signaling (`task_complete` tool)\n493: \n494: **Summary:** The mechanism by which an AI agent running inside opencode\n495: communicates iteration outcome back to the orchestrator. This is not\n496: operator-invoked; it is agent-invoked.\n497: \n498: ### Participating Modules\n499: \n500: - `.opencode/plugins/super-ralph.js` — registers the tool with the opencode\n501:   server\n502: - `src/opencode.ts` — scans session messages for tool-call results\n503: - `src/engine.ts` — interprets `CompletionResult` and applies loop logic\n504: \n505: ### Trigger\n506: \n507: An agent calls the `task_complete` tool during a session. The tool is\n508: registered by `.opencode/plugins/super-ralph.js` at server startup.\n509: \n510: ### Preconditions\n511: \n512: - The opencode server was started or attached by the engine.\n513: - The `super-ralph.js` plugin is installed in `.opencode/plugins/`.\n514: \n515: ### Normal Flow\n516: \n517: 1. The agent calls `task_complete({ status: \"<value>\", reason: \"<text>\" })`.\n518: 2. The plugin records the call result in the session message history.\n519: 3. When the session goes idle (`session.idle` SSE event), `runPrompt`\n520:    reads `session.messages()` and scans for a `task_complete` tool-call\n521:    result with `state.status === \"completed\"`.\n522: 4. The `input.status` value and optional `input.reason` become the\n523:    `CompletionResult` returned to the engine.\n524: 5. The engine increments the appropriate counter and evaluates whether to\n525:    continue the loop.\n526: \n527: ### Status Values and Engine Behavior\n528: \n529: | `status` value | Engine counter | Loop action |\n530: | --- | --- | --- |\n531: | `complete` | `completed++` | Continue (if `handleResult` returns `true`) |\n532: | `phase_done` | `completed++` | Stop (`handleResult` returns `false`) |\n533: | `blocked` | `skipped++` | Continue to next item |\n534: | `failed` | — | Apply failure strategy |\n535: \n536: ### Failure Outcomes\n537: \n538: | Condition | Observed Behavior |\n539: | --- | --- |\n540: | Agent never calls `task_complete` | Result is `stalled`; strategy applied |\n541: | Plugin not installed | `task_complete` tool unavailable; agent cannot signal; always `stalled` |\n542: | Session ends with `session.error` | Result is `error`; strategy applied |\n543: \n544: ### Observable Outputs and State Changes\n545: \n546: - No filesystem changes directly.\n547: - `CompletionResult` influences counters in `session.json`.\n548: - `status` and `reason` appended to `.super-ralph/progress.md` entry.\n549: - Loop continuation or termination determined.\n550: \n551: ---\n552: \n553: ## Cross-Workflow Relationships\n554: \n555: The three phase commands form a pipeline. Each phase reads what the previous\n556: phase wrote and writes what the next phase needs.\n557: \n558: ```text\n559: WF-02 reverse  -->  docs/specs/<name>.md\n560:                            |\n561:                            v\n562: WF-03 decompose -->  .beads/ (epic + child beads via br)\n563:                            |\n564:                            v\n565: WF-04 forward  -->  project source files + git commits\n566: ```\n567: \n568: WF-01 (`init`) must precede all phase commands. WF-05 (`status`) and\n569: WF-06 (`doctor`) are utility commands that can be run at any point.\n570: WF-07 (`task_complete`) is internal to every phase execution.\n571: \n572: ---\n573: \n574: ## Common Flags Across Phase Commands\n575: \n576: The following flags apply to `reverse`, `decompose`, and `forward`.\n577: \n578: | Flag | Effect |\n579: | --- | --- |\n580: | `--dry-run` | Shows what would run; no server started; no agent sessions |\n581: | `--model <id>` | Overrides model resolution for all iterations |\n582: | `--max-iterations <n>` | Caps the iteration count |\n583: | `--attach <url>` | Connects to an existing opencode server instead of spawning |\n584: \n585: ---\n586: \n587: ## Open Questions\n588: \n589: - Whether the agent's git commit is always a single commit per bead or\n590:   can span multiple commits is not confirmed by code inspection. [UNKNOWN]\n591: - The exact format of bead IDs returned by `br create` is not confirmed by\n592:   code inspection of `src/beads.ts`. [UNKNOWN]\n593: - The behavior when `--attach` is used and the external server shuts down\n594:   mid-run is not fully characterized. [UNKNOWN]\n\n(End of file - total 594 lines)\n</content>","title":"spec/workflows/core-workflows.md","metadata":{"preview":"# Core Workflows\n\n> Behavioral specification of the primary user-visible workflows in the\n> super-ralph agent framework, covering triggers, preconditions, normal flow,\n> alternate flows, failure outcomes, and observable outputs.\n\n**Source examined at commit:** `ecc95c0` (2026-02-27)\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis document captures the end-to-end behavior of each command a project\noperator can invoke. Each workflow section describes what the operator\nobserves from the outside: what to provide, what happens in sequence, what\nchanges on disk, and what can go wrong.\n\nFor internal module interactions see\n[`spec/architecture/overview.md`](../architecture/overview.md) and\n[`spec/architecture/runtime-lifecycle.md`](../architecture/runtime-lifecycle.md).\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772181445218,"end":1772181445226}}}}
